FAMERS IN MANNAR, VAVUNIYA AND MULLAITIVU DISTRICTS: PROVISION OF TOMEJC MANGO PLANTS AND
asked the Minister of Agriculture and Plantation Industries:
(a) Is he aware that the people residing in the Districts of Mannar, Vavuniya and Mullaitivu are in need of mango plants of TomEJC variety and solar-powered water pumps?
(b) Will he inform this House whether steps would be taken to -
(i) provide 90,000 mango plants to 900 farmer families, 300 farmer families in each district, in the Districts of Mannar, Vavuniya and Mullaitivu with 100 mango plants per farmer family; and

(ii) provide 1,500 solar-powered water pumps, each of which costs Rs. 330,000, under 70 per cent concession and 30 per cent beneficiary contribution to each of the above-mentioned districts in order to enhance the production capacity of farmers?

. We need a legal framework before we go into that process. We will be calling for EOIs once the legal framework is ready and we have an understanding as to what our requirements are. The International Atomic Energy Agency and other international agencies are all helping and assisting us to identify the best technology that is needed. Even the Hon. President, in his Policy Statement, had already stated that we should allow new technology to be adopted in our Long-term Generation Expansion Plan. So, we are not disregarding that proposal, but when and how it is going to be implemented is still under discussion. We have not committed ourselves to any country or any party on developing a nuclear power plant here in Sri Lanka. We have got many proposals and those will be evaluated in due course, but, first, we need to have the legal structure in place.

Hon. Member, the second thing you mentioned was about the Rs. 40 profit margin per litre of petrol. There is no Rs. 40 profit margin. I have tabled the profit and loss statement or the cost-reflective pricing formula in Parliament every month after the price revision had been done. Now, the 4 per cent margin accounts to about Rs. 13 to Rs. 14.

Dissanayake, since I am in charge of or leading the transformation of higher education, I would like to say that the nuclear scientists in this country are seriously discussing that matter at this point. As you know, the Indian Ocean is a nuclear-free ocean due to the policy that we have had. So, it concerns not only technology, but geopolitics is also involved. Some of our scientists have already been talking to Indian scientists and during the last two visits of the Finance Minister and the Foreign Minister of India, these discussions, not serious but footnote discussions, had taken place. India helped Bangladesh to build a nuclear plant for peaceful energy purposes. So, that is the model our President is also thinking on and we are on that path. Therefore, the Hon. Minister is right on that and from an intellectual point of view or from nuclear scientists point of view, we are working on that. Thank you, Hon. Member, for raising that.

The Constitutional Council established under the Seventeenth Amendment, is a part of the Executive and is attributed executive power. Thus the Council would come within the executive organ of Government in regard to Article 4 (d) of the Constitution referred to above. It is therefore the duty of the Constitutional Council to respect, secure and advance the fundamental rights which are declared and recognized by the Constitution. The functions of the Constitutional Council would come within the framework of executive action as provided for in terms of Article 17 of the Constitution.

STAFF OF SRI LANKA INSURANCE CORPORATION LTD.: SALARIES, ALLOWANCES AND INSURANCE ENTITLEMENT
asked the Minister of Finance, Economic Stabilization and National Policy:

(a) Will he inform this House of - (i) the subsidiaries and affiliated institutions of the Sri Lanka Insurance Corporation Ltd.; (ii) the number of approved staff for the Sri Lanka Insurance Corporation Ltd.; (iii) the number of executive and junior employees of that staff, separately; (iv) the monthly salaries and allowances related to each position of executive and junior staff, separately; and (v) the value of the insurance claim provided for each employee of the Sri Lanka Insurance Corporation Ltd. and his/her family, separately?
, , ( - , ) (The Hon. Ranil Wickremesinghe - President, Minister of Defence and Minister of Finance, Economic Stabilization and National Policies)
(a) (i) The subsidiaries and affiliates of Sri Lanka Insurance Corporation Limited are as follows:
Senior management who have been seconded by Management Services Rakshana Private Limited.
related to each position of executive and junior staff are given separately in Annexes I* and II*.
(v) The value of the insurance claim provided
for each employee of the SLIC and his/ her family separately is as follows:

Medical Cover - Medical cover can be obtained for all employees for a value of Rs. 1.4 million. The employee has to pay Rs. 800.00 and the company contributes Rs. 1600.00 per member (This covers the staff member, spouse and children)
Death Benefit - The company pays a lump sum amount at the time of a death based on the remaining number of years to retire.
